<$fill $name="body">

!! Do I need to set the type on every `.md` file?

No. Any `.md` file with YAML frontmatter (`---` delimiters) is auto-detected at boot. The type `text/x-frontmattered-markdown` only matters for ''saving'' ‚Äî it tells TiddlyWiki to use YAML frontmatter format instead of `.meta` sidecar.

!! Why does the plugin suppress syncer events?

Without suppression, the syncer sees the re-parsed tiddlers as "changed" and tries to delete the original files and re-save them. This corrupts the `.md` files by replacing YAML frontmatter with TiddlyWiki's native format.

!! Why two passes?

Pass 1 handles files discovered by TiddlyWiki's boot scanner (in `boot.files`). Pass 2 handles tiddlers loaded via `tiddlywiki.files` directives ‚Äî these don't appear in `boot.files` but may still contain YAML frontmatter that needs parsing.

!! Can I use frontmatter with `tiddlywiki.files`?

Yes. Define a `tiddlywiki.files` entry with a clean title. The frontmatter plugin's Pass 2 detects the YAML block and re-parses the fields while keeping the assigned title.

!! What happens to existing `text/x-markdown` tiddlers?

They are unaffected. The plugin only processes files that have YAML frontmatter blocks. Regular markdown tiddlers continue to use `.meta` sidecars.

</$fill>
</$transclude>
