<$fill $name="body">

!! What it does

The frontmatter plugin lets `.md` files carry their tiddler metadata as YAML frontmatter instead of requiring `.meta` sidecar files. This makes markdown files self-contained and compatible with external tools (Claude Code, VS Code, Obsidian, etc.) that understand YAML frontmatter natively.

!! How it works

When a tiddler has type `text/x-frontmattered-markdown`, it is saved to disk as:

```
---
tags:
  - documentation
  - example
created: "20260330120000000"
modified: "20260330120000000"
type: text/x-frontmattered-markdown
---

# Markdown content here
```

At boot, the startup module auto-detects ''any'' `.md` file with a `---` YAML frontmatter block and re-parses it ‚Äî no explicit type annotation needed. This means external tools can create `.md` files with frontmatter and TiddlyWiki will pick them up automatically.

!! Key design decisions

* ''Auto-detect over opt-in'' ‚Äî any `.md` with frontmatter is re-parsed, not just files with `text/x-frontmattered-markdown`
* ''Syncer suppression'' ‚Äî change events are suppressed during re-parse to prevent the syncer from deleting originals and re-saving in TW format
* ''Two-pass architecture'' ‚Äî first pass handles `boot.files` (filesystem-scanned), second pass handles `tiddlywiki.files`-loaded tiddlers
* ''Title priority'' ‚Äî frontmatter `title` > existing clean title (from `tiddlywiki.files`) > derived from filepath
* ''Runs before syncer'' ‚Äî startup module runs `before: ["startup"]` so the syncer's initial snapshot sees already-fixed state

</$fill>
</$transclude>
